**Anarchism in the United Kingdom**

Anarchism in the United Kingdom, if one can call it that, initially bobbed along in the wake of [religious dissent](/English_Dissenters) that had been stirring since the [Protestant Reformation](/English_Reformation). You could squint and see early glimmers among the more radical republican factions during the [English Civil War](/English_Civil_War). After the [Stuart Restoration](/Stuart_Restoration), these ideas fermented in the less respectable corners of [radical Whiggery](/Radical_Whigs). It's almost amusing that [Edmund Burke](/Edmund_Burke), a Whig politician no less, was the first to articulate something resembling [anarchist ideas](/A_Vindication_of_Natural_Society). This intellectual undercurrent eventually shaped the rather more coherent [political philosophy](/Philosophical_anarchism) of [William Godwin](/William_Godwin), who, with his 1793 book [Enquiry Concerning Political Justice](/Enquiry_Concerning_Political_Justice), effectively birthed modern anarchism.

The real push towards organized [socialism](/Socialism), moving away from mere [radicalism](/Radicalism_(historical)), kicked off in the 1860s. The [International Workingmen's Association](/International_Workingmen%27s_Association) (IWA) was established, bringing together various workers' groups demanding everything from reform to outright liberty. By the 1870s, the continent's anarchist ideas had seeped into Britain. The founding of the [Labour Emancipation League](/Labour_Emancipation_League) (LEL) in 1881 marked the true beginning of the organized anarchist movement on this damp island. The LEL was a stepping stone, crucial in the formation of the [Socialist League](/Socialist_League_(UK,_1885)), which, by 1888, found itself under the sway of the anarchist [Frank Kitz](/Frank_Kitz).

Through the turn of the 20th century, anarchism was kept alive, barely, by publications like the Socialist League's [Commonweal](/Commonweal_(newspaper)) and [Peter Kropotkin](/Peter_Kropotkin)'s [Freedom](/Freedom_(British_newspaper)). [Anarcho-communism](/Anarcho-communism) gained traction during the tumultuous [Revolutions of 1917–1923](/Revolutions_of_1917%E2%80%931923). In Glasgow, the anarchist [Guy Aldred](/Guy_Aldred) was busy setting up the [Anti-Parliamentary Communist Federation](/Anti-Parliamentary_Communist_Federation) and later the [United Socialist Movement](/United_Socialist_Movement). Post-[Spanish Civil War](/Spanish_Civil_War), the rise of [anarcho-syndicalism](/Anarcho-syndicalism) eventually led to the creation of the [Solidarity Federation](/Solidarity_Federation) in 1950. The 1980s saw another surge, this time for anarcho-communism, with the founding of groups like [Class War](/Class_War) and the [Anarchist Federation](/Anarchist_Federation_(Britain)).

### History

Historians, like [Peter Marshall](/Peter_Marshall_(author,_born_1946)), have traced the origins of British anarchism back to the rather chaotic [Peasants' Revolt](/Peasants%27_Revolt) of 1381. The common folk, the [yeomen](/Yeoman), were understandably riled by the [Bad Parliament's poll tax](/Bad_Parliament%27s_poll_tax), fearing it was a ploy by the [nobility](/British_nobility) to drag them back into [serfdom](/Serfdom). Their agitation was amplified by the sermons of a radical priest, [John Ball](/John_Ball_(priest)). He preached of the [Garden of Eden](/Garden_of_Eden) as a [state of nature](/State_of_nature) devoid of [class stratification](/Class_stratification), decrying [private property](/Private_property) and [social inequality](/Social_inequality), advocating for [common ownership](/Common_ownership) and a truly [classless society](/Classless_society). Led by their "captain," [Wat Tyler](/Wat_Tyler), a horde of 100,000 peasants marched from [Essex](/Essex) to [London](/London), gathering support along the way. King [Richard II](/Richard_II) made promises of freedom, but this didn't stop the rebels from demolishing the [Savoy Palace](/Savoy_Palace), freeing prisoners, and executing [Simon Sudbury](/Simon_Sudbury), the [Archbishop of Canterbury](/Archbishop_of_Canterbury). With the capital in their grasp, they laid out their demands: [wage labour](/Wage_labour), an end to [feudal duties](/Feudal_duties), and the establishment of a [free market](/Free_market). The King, in meetings with rebel leaders, seemed to agree to most of it. Tyler pushed for the abolition of serfdom and greater [liberty](/Liberty) and [social equality](/Social_equality). His more radical lieutenant, [Jack Straw](/Jack_Straw_(rebel_leader)), allegedly suggested the extermination of the nobility and clergy. &#91;3&#93; But these demands were short-lived. [William Walworth](/William_Walworth), the [Lord Mayor of London](/Lord_Mayor_of_London), dispatched Tyler and Straw, the King reneged on his promises, and the revolt was crushed. &#91;4&#93; Yet, Ball's egalitarian ideas persisted, notably resurfacing in [William Morris](/William_Morris)' 1888 novel, [A Dream of John Ball](/A_Dream_of_John_Ball). &#91;5&#93;

#### The English Revolution

For centuries, [feudalism](/Feudalism) had cemented a rigidly [hierarchical society](/Hierarchical_organization) where individual desires were secondary to the [divine right of kings](/Divine_right_of_kings). The [Renaissance](/Renaissance) and [Reformation](/Reformation) began to shift this, placing a nascent emphasis on the individual as an autonomous being with inherent rights. It was during the [English Revolution](/English_Revolution) that these notions of individual rights truly intertwined with older calls for [liberty](/Liberty) and [social equality](/Social_equality), giving rise to what could be recognised as early [anarchist tendencies](/Precursors_to_anarchism). &#91;6&#93; By the 16th century, the word "[anarchy](/Anarchy)" was almost exclusively synonymous with [disorder](/Civil_disorder) and [lawlessness](/Lawlessness). The label "[anarchist](/Anarchism)" was a convenient insult hurled at anyone who dared to disrupt the established order or question authority. &#91;7&#93;

The Declaration and Standard of the Levellers of England.

In the lead-up to the [English Civil War](/English_Civil_War), radical republican and democratic ideas began to circulate, challenging institutions like the [monarchy](/Monarchy_of_the_United_Kingdom), the [church](/Church_of_England), and [feudalism](/Feudalism_in_England). In December 1640, a petition signed by 15,000 Londoners, the "[Root and Branch petition](/Root_and_Branch_petition)", demanded the abolition of the [episcopacy](/Episcopal_polity). This was promptly labelled "absolute Anarchism" by the royalist MP [Edward Dering](/Sir_Edward_Dering,_1st_Baronet). &#91;8&#93; When the bill failed to pass, [anti-clerical](/Anti-clericalism) riots erupted in [London](/London), &#91;9&#93; ultimately forcing [Charles I](/Charles_I_of_England) to flee, along with his supporters, allowing Parliament to enact anti-clerical legislation. &#91;10&#93;

These escalating tensions ignited the [First English Civil War](/First_English_Civil_War), pitting [Parliamentarians](/Roundhead) against [Cavalier](/Cavalier) royalist forces. Following their victory, a radical group known as the [Levellers](/Levellers) drafted a series of manifestos outlining a new constitution. These proposals were debated fiercely among parliamentary troops, as the Levellers advocated for [progressive taxation](/Progressive_tax), [universal manhood suffrage](/Universal_manhood_suffrage), and [equality before the law](/Equality_before_the_law). &#91;11&#93; [Oliver Cromwell](/Oliver_Cromwell), however, rejected these [radical democratic](/Radical_democracy) ideas, accusing the Levellers of promoting the [cantonalist](/Cantons_of_Switzerland) practices of the [Swiss Confederacy](/Old_Swiss_Confederacy) and warning that such policies would inevitably descend into "anarchy". &#91;12&#93; The Levellers, for their part, denied this, maintaining their belief in a form of "[good government](/Good_government)". &#91;13&#93;

After Parliament's triumph in the [Second English Civil War](/Second_English_Civil_War), dissenters were purged from the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_England), and [Charles I](/Charles_I_of_England) was executed. Power consolidated in the hands of the [Grandees](/Grandee) of the [New Model Army](/New_Model_Army). Unwilling to implement the Levellers' radical agenda, they instead turned towards [mysticism](/Christian_mysticism) and the establishment of a [Puritan](/Puritans) religious order. This new climate of Christian mysticism, however, gave rise to various [anti-authoritarian](/Anti-authoritarian) strains, with numerous [English Dissenters](/English_Dissenters) breaking away from the [Church of England](/Church_of_England). Among them were the [Quakers](/Quakers), [Ranters](/Ranters), [Anabaptists](/British_Anabaptism), [Familists](/Familia_Caritatis), and the [Diggers](/Diggers). &#91;14&#93; Historians have pointed to the Ranters and Diggers as "anarchists" due to their radical egalitarianism and [communist practices](/Pre-Marxist_communism). &#91;15&#93; The Diggers, attempting to create an egalitarian society of small agrarian communities, occupied common land for farming, but their settlements were eventually suppressed by the authorities of the [Commonwealth](/Commonwealth_of_England). &#91;16&#93;

By 1653, the [Rump Parliament](/Rump_Parliament) was dissolved by the New Model Army, and the republican Commonwealth gave way to a [military dictatorship](/Rule_of_the_Major-Generals) known as [The Protectorate](/The_Protectorate), with Cromwell at its head. Following Cromwell's death, Parliament was reconvened and a [Convention](/Convention_Parliament_(1660)) was held, leading to the [restoration](/Stuart_Restoration) of the monarchy. Within a few decades, the [Stuart](/House_of_Stuart) kingdoms of [England](/Kingdom_of_England) and [Scotland](/Kingdom_of_Scotland) were formally united into the [Kingdom of Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain), and the [British Empire](/British_Empire) was established. The gradual spread of the [Age of Enlightenment](/Age_of_Enlightenment) to Britain, coupled with the advent of the [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution), brought about significant societal shifts. These changes provided the fertile ground for the early conceptualization of a formalized [anarchist philosophy](/Philosophical_anarchism).

#### The British Enlightenment

The [Glorious Revolution](/Glorious_Revolution) of 1688 firmly cemented a [constitutional monarchy](/Constitutional_monarchy) with [parliamentary sovereignty](/Parliamentary_sovereignty) in Britain. [John Locke](/John_Locke) notably defended this revolution, his arguments for democratic governance laying the groundwork for [classical liberalism](/Classical_liberalism). Locke posited that while the "[state of nature](/State_of_nature)" represented a condition of absolute [liberty](/Liberty) and [social equality](/Social_equality), individual competition led to [instability](/Instability), necessitating a government to safeguard "life, liberty and property." This led to his concept of a [social contract](/Social_contract) between the people and their government, granting the latter the authority to create laws and protect [private property](/Private_property). The [Lockean proviso](/Lockean_proviso) thus marked a transition from the [traditionalist conservatism](/Traditionalist_conservatism) of the established [landed gentry](/Landed_gentry) (who would become known as [Tories](/Tories_(British_political_party))) to the [propertarianism](/Propertarianism) of the burgeoning [middle classes](/Middle_class) (later the [Whigs](/Whigs_(British_political_party))). &#91;17&#93; By the dawn of the 18th century, Lockean liberalism began to evolve into [libertarianism](/Libertarianism), which placed a premium on individual freedom within the new constitutional framework. &#91;18&#93;

[Jonathan Swift](/Jonathan_Swift), despite his conservative leanings and misanthropic outlook, became an early proponent of [Enlightenment ideals](/Age_of_Enlightenment) and a critic of [British rule in Ireland](/British_rule_in_Ireland). His 1726 novel, [Gulliver's Travels](/Gulliver%27s_Travels), satirized the prevailing [social mores](/Social_mores) of his time, railing against [social inequality](/Social_inequality) and the [Protestant work ethic](/Protestant_work_ethic), among other issues. &#91;19&#93; In Book IV, Swift introduces the [Houyhnhnms](/Houyhnhnms), a race of intelligent [horses](/Horse) who believed society could be self-governing through [reason](/Reason) and lived in a form of [primitive communism](/Primitive_communism). &#91;20&#93; Their only central governing body was an advisory council that met quadrennially to coordinate resource distribution, possessing no power to enforce its decisions. &#91;21&#93; Swift's vision of a [stateless society](/Stateless_society) would later influence [William Godwin](/William_Godwin)'s anarchist philosophy, though it would also draw criticism from [George Orwell](/George_Orwell) as "[totalitarian](/Totalitarianism)", leading Orwell to label Swift a "Tory anarchist". &#91;22&#93;

[Edmund Burke](/Edmund_Burke), a [Radical Whig](/Radical_Whigs) politician, authored [A Vindication of Natural Society](/A_Vindication_of_Natural_Society), an early literary manifestation of [philosophical anarchism](/Philosophical_anarchism). Following the [French Revolution](/French_Revolution), his political stance shifted dramatically, and he became a prominent advocate for [conservative liberalism](/Conservative_liberalism) and [traditionalist conservatism](/Traditionalist_conservatism).

[Thomas Paine](/Thomas_Paine), whose revolutionary tracts [Common Sense](/Common_Sense) and [Rights of Man](/Rights_of_Man) provided foundational arguments for the development of modern [libertarianism](/Libertarianism).

In 1756, [Edmund Burke](/Edmund_Burke) presented a defense of the "state of nature" in [A Vindication of Natural Society](/A_Vindication_of_Natural_Society). He depicted human society as governed by reason until the advent of the [state](/State_(polity)) and the [episcopacy](/Episcopal_polity). The historian [Peter Marshall](/Peter_Marshall_(author,_born_1946)) described this work as "one of the most powerful arguments for anarchist society made in the eighteenth century." Burke condemned the state as the root cause of all [social conflict](/Social_conflict) and [war](/War). He argued that the division of humanity into distinct [nationalities](/Nationality) fostered [bigotry](/Bigotry), and that [social stratification](/Social_stratification) led to the [concentration of wealth](/Distribution_of_wealth) among those who did not earn it. &#91;23&#93; While preferring [democracy](/Democracy) over [despotism](/Despotism) and [aristocracy](/Aristocracy), Burke still found existing governments wanting, ultimately calling for a complete rejection of both church and state to reclaim "[perfect liberty](/Anarchy)". &#91;24&#93; Burke later embraced [conservatism](/Conservatism) and disavowed his *Vindication*, claiming it was a satirical critique of the parliamentary opposition leader [Henry St John](/Henry_St_John,_1st_Viscount_Bolingbroke). Nonetheless, the text profoundly influenced the anarchist philosophy of [William Godwin](/William_Godwin) and the [libertarian socialism](/Libertarian_socialism) of [George Holyoake](/George_Holyoake). &#91;25&#93;

The [American Revolution](/American_Revolution) brought [Thomas Paine](/Thomas_Paine) to prominence. He advocated for [women's rights](/Women%27s_rights), the [abolition of slavery](/Abolitionism), and the prevention of [cruelty to animals](/Cruelty_to_animals). His 1776 pamphlet, [Common Sense](/Common_Sense), garnered significant attention with its calls for the [independence](/Independence) of the [Thirteen Colonies](/Thirteen_Colonies) and a [people's war](/People%27s_war) against the [British Empire](/British_Empire), hoping America would serve as an inspiration for future global revolutions. &#91;26&#93; Inspired by the [spontaneous order](/Spontaneous_order) that emerged after the colonial government's collapse, Paine clearly distinguished between society and the state, asserting that "society in every state is a blessing, but government even in its best state is but a necessary evil; in its worse state an intolerable one." However, Paine still supported the establishment of a [limited government](/Limited_government) through a social contract, enshrined in a written [constitution](/Constitution) that would guarantee the rights to "[Life, Liberty and the pursuit of Happiness](/Life,_Liberty_and_the_pursuit_of_Happiness)". &#91;27&#93; The conclusion of the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War) was swiftly followed by the [French Revolution](/French_Revolution), and Paine transferred his revolutionary fervor to Europe. &#91;28&#93;

Edmund Burke's publication of [Reflections on the Revolution in France](/Reflections_on_the_Revolution_in_France) ignited a fierce [pamphlet war](/Pamphlet_war) in Britain, known as the "[Revolution Controversy](/Revolution_Controversy)". &#91;25&#93; In this work, Burke presented a traditionalist conservative perspective on government, cautioning against radical reforms that he feared would shift power from the clergy and nobility to the "[swinish multitude](/Mass_politics)." &#91;28&#93; The [Radicals](/Radicals_(UK)), many of whom had been influenced by Burke's earlier writings, eagerly joined the debate. [Mary Wollstonecraft](/Mary_Wollstonecraft), a feminist, was among the first to respond. Her works, [Vindication of the Rights of Men](/A_Vindication_of_the_Rights_of_Men) and later [Vindication of the Rights of Woman](/A_Vindication_of_the_Rights_of_Woman), attacked [class stratification](/Class_stratification), [economic inequality](/Economic_inequality), and [gender inequality](/Gender_inequality), advocating for a reformed government to protect [natural rights](/Natural_rights_and_legal_rights). Thomas Paine followed Wollstonecraft's contributions with his own [Rights of Man](/Rights_of_Man). According to Peter Marshall, Paine's work displayed a "libertarian sensibility [that] took him to the borders of anarchism." &#91;25&#93;

Paine sided with the "swinish multitude," criticizing Burke for prioritizing the "authority of the dead" over [individual rights](/Individual_and_group_rights). He adapted Lockean liberalism towards [libertarianism](/Libertarianism) and [direct democracy](/Direct_democracy). &#91;29&#93; To safeguard natural rights, he again proposed a limited government, one subservient to the people's authority and devoid of independent power, aiming for "[the good of all](/Utilitarianism)". &#91;30&#93; In Part II of his pamphlet, Paine edged closer to anarchism by suggesting that societal order would persist even without government, stating that "society [in] every state is a blessing, but government even in its best state is but a necessary evil; in its worse state an intolerable one." He argued that order stemmed from human nature, inherently good but corrupted by established governments, and that individuals were primarily guided by their own [common interest](/Enlightened_self-interest) rather than [legal codes](/Code_of_law). &#91;31&#93; Drawing on British history, Paine concluded by advocating for a [self-governing society](/Self-governance), asserting, "the instant formal government is abolished, society begins to act. A general association takes place, and common interest produces common security." He viewed the ideal government as a limited entity, solely tasked with securing individual natural rights, and pointed to the nascent [federal government of the United States](/Federal_government_of_the_United_States) as a model. &#91;32&#93; Despite his strong libertarian leanings, Paine's ultimate commitment to [constitutionalism](/Constitutionalism), [republicanism](/Republicanism), and [propertarianism](/Propertarianism) distinguished him from modern anarchism. &#91;33&#93;

[William Godwin](/William_Godwin), the first modern proponent of [philosophical anarchism](/Philosophical_anarchism), as articulated in his [Enquiry Concerning Political Justice](/Enquiry_Concerning_Political_Justice) (1793).

It was during the Revolution Controversy that [William Godwin](/William_Godwin) published [Enquiry Concerning Political Justice](/Enquiry_Concerning_Political_Justice), presenting the first clear exposition of [philosophical anarchism](/Philosophical_anarchism) and declaring that all government should be abolished. &#91;34&#93; Though the book was expensive upon release, preventing Prime Minister [William Pitt](/William_Pitt_the_Younger) from easily banning it, many British workers pooled their resources to purchase it by subscription. Pirated copies circulated widely in Ireland and Scotland, and Godwin eventually lowered the price. &#91;35&#93; When Pitt's government began prosecuting figures within the [British radical movement](/Radicalism_(historical)) in 1794, Godwin defended the accused radicals, ultimately securing their acquittal. &#91;36&#93; Despite his disillusionment following the [defeat of the French Revolution](/Coup_of_18_Brumaire), Godwin's influence extended to the next generation of radicals. His son-in-law, the renowned poet [Percy Bysshe Shelley](/Percy_Bysshe_Shelley), infused much of Godwin's anarchist philosophy into his verse, while his disciple [Robert Owen](/Robert_Owen) became a foundational figure in [British socialism](/History_of_the_socialist_movement_in_the_United_Kingdom). After Godwin's death, *Political Justice* continued to inspire the [Chartists](/Chartism) and [Owenites](/Owenism), who published new editions, as well as the [Ricardian socialism](/Ricardian_socialism) of [Thomas Hodgskin](/Thomas_Hodgskin) and [William Thompson](/William_Thompson_(philosopher)). This, in turn, influenced the [Marxist theory](/Marxist_philosophy) of the "[withering away of the state](/Withering_away_of_the_state)". &#91;37&#93;

However, by the turn of the 19th century, British radicals had not yet adopted the term "anarchist" for themselves. Even Godwin associated "anarchy" with disorder, though he considered it preferable to [despotism](/Despotism), seeing it as a reflection of "true [liberty](/Liberty)". Nonetheless, followers of Godwin's philosophy began to be labelled as "anarchists," most notably by the Tory statesman [George Canning](/George_Canning), who denounced William Godwin, Thomas Paine, and the reformer [John Thelwall](/John_Thelwall) as anarchists in the [Anti-Jacobin Review](/Anti-Jacobin_Review). &#91;38&#93;

### 19th century to World War II

The British labour movement began to coalesce in the early 19th century. Spearheaded by the utopian socialist [Robert Owen](/Robert_Owen), a follower of [William Godwin](/William_Godwin), the [Grand National Consolidated Trades Union](/Grand_National_Consolidated_Trades_Union) played a role in the early development of [syndicalism](/Syndicalism) in Britain. The nonconformist priest [William Benbow](/William_Benbow) popularized the concept of the [general strike](/General_strike) as a tool for [social revolution](/Social_revolution). However, the rise of the [Chartists](/Chartists) imbued the British labour movement with a predominantly [reformist](/Reformism) character, largely focused on [parliamentary politics](/Parliamentary_system). &#91;38&#93;

The introduction of [classical anarchism](/History_of_anarchism) to Britain occurred with the arrival of [migrant workers](/Migrant_workers) and [asylum seekers](/Asylum_seeker) in London, following the [Revolutions of 1848](/Revolutions_of_1848). Over the ensuing decades, isolated individuals gradually formed into small political groups, such as the [Rose Street Club](/Rose_Street_Club) in [Soho](/Soho). This process intensified when [Johann Most](/Johann_Most) relocated to London and began publishing his newspaper [Freiheit](/Freiheit_(1879)). The paper was eventually shut down and its operations moved to the United States after Most's associates expressed support for the [Phoenix Park Murders]. &#91;39&#93;

By 1881, the shift of British revolutionary socialists towards anarchism solidified with the establishment of the [Labour Emancipation League](/Labour_Emancipation_League) (LEL). The LEL quickly garnered support for its [libertarian socialist](/Libertarian_socialism) platform among the workers of London's [East End](/East_End), explicitly rejecting all forms of government, before merging into the [Social Democratic Federation](/Social_Democratic_Federation) (SDF). &#91;40&#93; However, the [authoritarianism](/Authoritarianism) of the SDF's leader, [Henry Hyndman](/Henry_Hyndman), led to a split, resulting in the formation of the [Socialist League](/Socialist_League_(UK,_1885)) (SL) by a group of libertarian socialists centered around [William Morris](/William_Morris). Although Morris was a staunch anti-parliamentarian, he eventually left the SL after its anarchist faction gained prominence in 1887. This led to a noticeable radicalization of the League's publications under [H. B. Samuels](/H._B._Samuels). &#91;41&#93;

Poster advertising a meeting in support of the Walsall Anarchists

Other anarchist currents also emerged around this period: [individualist anarchism](/Individualist_anarchism), championed by [Henry Seymour](/Henry_Seymour_(secularist)) in his publication [The Anarchist](/The_Anarchist_(newspaper)); [anarcho-communism](/Anarcho-communism), propagated by [Peter Kropotkin](/Peter_Kropotkin) through his newspaper [Freedom](/Freedom_(British_newspaper)); and [Jewish anarchism](/Jewish_anarchism), which coalesced around the [Yiddish language](/Yiddish_language) journal [Arbeter Fraynd](/Arbeter_Fraynd). &#91;42&#93; Anarchist themes also found their way into popular literature. William Morris' [News from Nowhere](/News_from_Nowhere) depicted a utopian society, and [Oscar Wilde](/Oscar_Wilde)'s [The Soul of Man Under Socialism](/The_Soul_of_Man_Under_Socialism) championed [individualism](/Individualism). Libertarian ideas were also defended by writers such as [George Bernard Shaw](/George_Bernard_Shaw), [Edward Carpenter](/Edward_Carpenter), and [Henry Stephens Salt](/Henry_Stephens_Salt). &#91;43&#93;

However, anarchism failed to capture the imagination of the more reform-minded labour movement. [Anarcho-syndicalism](/Anarcho-syndicalism) only began to develop at the turn of the 20th century. In the 1910s, [Tom Mann](/Tom_Mann)'s [Industrial Syndicalist Education League](/Industrial_Syndicalist_Education_League) attempted to foster the creation of [industrial unions](/Industrial_unions) in Britain, advocating for direct [class conflict](/Class_conflict) with the ultimate goal of [workers' control](/Workers%27_control). The influence of anarcho-syndicalism waned significantly after [World War I](/World_War_I), which also caused a [split](/Internationalist%E2%80%93defencist_schism) within the anarchist movement itself. &#91;44&#93; Despite the efforts of anarcho-communists like [Guy Aldred](/Guy_Aldred) to sustain the movement, by the mid-1920s, the British anarchist movement had largely dissolved, with only a few scattered groups remaining in urban centers. &#91;45&#93; The outbreak of the [Spanish Civil War](/Spanish_Civil_War) provided a catalyst for a revival, fostering a new generation of anarchists by the time [World War II](/World_War_II) commenced. &#91;46&#93;

### Post-war era

In early 1945, when [Vernon Richards](/Vernon_Richards) and three other editors were arrested for attempting "to undermine the affections of members of His Majesty's Forces," &#91;47&#93; prominent figures such as [Benjamin Britten](/Benjamin_Britten), [E. M. Forster](/E._M._Forster), [Augustus John](/Augustus_John), [George Orwell](/George_Orwell), [Herbert Read](/Herbert_Read) (serving as chairman), [Osbert Sitwell](/Osbert_Sitwell), and [George Woodcock](/George_Woodcock) established the [Freedom Defence Committee](/Freedom_Defence_Committee). Their stated aim was "to uphold the essential liberty of individuals and organizations, and to defend those who are persecuted for exercising their rights to freedom of speech, writing and action." &#91;48&#93;

The [Syndicalist Workers' Federation](/Syndicalist_Workers%27_Federation) was an active syndicalist group in post-war Britain, &#91;49&#93; and a precursor to the [Solidarity Federation](/Solidarity_Federation). Formed in 1950 by former members of the dissolved [Anarchist Federation of Britain](/Anarchist_Federation_of_Britain) (AFB), the SWF adopted a more explicitly syndicalist, worker-focused strategy from its inception, unlike the AFB which, while influenced by anarcho-syndicalism, wasn't strictly syndicalist. The group affiliated with the [International Workers' Association](/IWA%E2%80%93AIT). During the [Franco era](/Francoist_Spain), it provided significant support to the Spanish resistance and the clandestine [CNT](/Confederaci%C3%B3n_Nacional_del_Trabajo) anarcho-syndicalist union, which had been instrumental in the 1936 [Spanish Revolution](/Spanish_Revolution_of_1936) and the subsequent [Civil War](/Spanish_Civil_War) against the right-wing military coup supported by [Nazi Germany](/Nazi_Germany) and [Fascist Italy](/Kingdom_of_Italy). The SWF experienced initial success, but declined after [Tom Brown](/Tom_Brown_(anarchist)), a long-standing and dedicated member, was forced to withdraw from activism. By 1979, it was reduced to a single branch in [Manchester](/Manchester). The SWF eventually dissolved into the Direct Action Movement. Its archives are held by the [International Institute of Social History](/International_Institute_of_Social_History), with some publications digitized on [libcom.org](/Libcom.org).

[Colin Ward](/Colin_Ward) served as an editor for the British [anarchist](/Anarchist) newspaper *Freedom* from 1947 to 1960. He then founded and edited the monthly [anarchist](/Anarchist) journal *Anarchy* from 1961 until its cessation in 1970, producing 118 issues. This publication should not be confused with a later, shorter-lived magazine of the same name, sometimes referred to as *Anarchy* (Second Series), which was produced by a different group. &#91;50&#93; &#91;51&#93;

#### Anarchists in London

The editorial team for *Freedom* over the years included individuals such as [Jack Robinson](/Jack_Robinson_(anarchist)), Pete Turner, [Colin Ward](/Colin_Ward), [Nicolas Walter](/Nicolas_Walter), [Alan Albon](/Alan_Albon), [John Rety](/John_Rety), Nino Staffa, Dave Mansell, Gillian Fleming, Mary Canipa, [Philip Sansom](/Philip_Sansom), and [Arthur Moyse](/Arthur_Moyse), among many others. [Clifford Harper](/Clifford_Harper) maintained a loose association with the publication for three decades.

The prominent [anarcho-pacifist](/Anarcho-pacifist) writer and gerontologist [Alex Comfort](/Alex_Comfort) described himself as an "aggressive anti-militarist." He argued that pacifism was "solely upon the historical theory of anarchism." &#91;52&#93; &#91;53&#93; A committed member of the [Peace Pledge Union](/Peace_Pledge_Union) (PPU) and the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament, Comfort had been a [conscientious objector](/Conscientious_objector) during [World War II](/World_War_II). In 1951, he was a signatory of the Authors’ World Peace Appeal. He later resigned from its committee, citing the growing influence of Soviet sympathizers within the AWPA. &#91;54&#93; Later in the decade, he actively supported the Direct Action Committee against Nuclear War. As a prominent member of the [Committee of 100](/Committee_of_100_(United_Kingdom)), he was imprisoned for a month, alongside [Bertrand Russell](/Bertrand_Russell) and others, for refusing to be bound over to refrain from participating in a Trafalgar Square protest in September 1961. Comfort authored *Peace and Disobedience* (1946), one of many pamphlets he wrote for [Peace News](/Peace_News) and the PPU, and *Authority and Delinquency in the Modern State* (1950). &#91;52&#93; He engaged in public correspondence with [George Orwell](/George_Orwell), defending pacifism in the open letter/poem "Letter to an American Visitor," under the [pseudonym](/Pseudonym) "Obadiah Hornbrooke." &#91;55&#93; Comfort's 1972 book, [The Joy of Sex](/The_Joy_of_Sex), brought him international fame and considerable wealth. He expressed regret that this led to him being known as "Dr. Sex," overshadowing his numerous other works. &#91;56&#93;

#### Anarchists in London

On the final day of July 1964, an 18-year-old [Stuart Christie](/Stuart_Christie) departed London for [Paris](/Paris). There, he acquired [plastic explosives](/Plastic_explosives) from the anarchist organization [Defensa Interior](/Defensa_Interior) &#91;57&#93; and proceeded to [Madrid](/Madri) on a mission to assassinate [General Francisco Franco](/Francisco_Franco). This endeavor was one of at least 30 attempts on the dictator's life. Upon his release, Christie continued his activism within the anarchist movement in the United Kingdom. Alongside [Miguel Garcia Garcia](/Miguel_Garc%C3%ADa_Garc%C3%ADa) – who had spent 22 years imprisoned by Franco's regime and whom Christie met in Madrid's [Carabanchel Prison] &#91;58&#93; &#91;59&#93; – and [Albert Meltzer](/Albert_Meltzer), Christie re-established the [Anarchist Black Cross](/Anarchist_Black_Cross) and *Black Flag* newspaper. He was acquitted of involvement with [The Angry Brigade](/The_Angry_Brigade) and founded the publishing house Cienfuegos Press (later Refract Publications). For several years, he operated this press from the remote island of [Sanday](/Sanday,_Orkney) in the [Orkney](/Orkney) archipelago, where he also edited and published a local newspaper, *The Free-Winged Eagle*. Christie co-authored *The Floodgates of Anarchy* with Meltzer and later *We, the Anarchists! A study of the [Iberian Anarchist Federation](/Federaci%C3%B3n_Anarquista_Ib%C3%A9rica) (FAI) 1927-1937* (2000). &#91;60&#93;

#### Squatting since the 1960s

In November 1968, a group of homeless families, joined by [anarchists](/Anarchism) (some with prior experience in [direct action](/Direct_action) during the [nuclear disarmament](/Nuclear_disarmament) campaigns), launched the London Squatters Campaign with the goal of securing "family housing." &#91;61&#93; &#91;62&#93; The campaign's first significant action involved occupying 17 houses in the London borough of [Redbridge](/London_Borough_of_Redbridge). &#91;63&#93; &#91;64&#93; After successfully resisting eviction attempts by private bailiffs, and with considerable media attention, the council agreed to grant the use of empty properties under license. &#91;65&#93; &#58;&#8202;19–21&#8202; [Colin Ward](/Colin_Ward), who became the Education Officer for the [Town and Country Planning Association](/Town_and_Country_Planning_Association) in 1971, &#91;66&#93; provided a philosophical and political defense for this practice in his 1976 work, *Housing: an anarchist approach*. &#91;67&#93;

By the late 1970s, estimates placed the number of squatters in England and Wales at 50,000, with 30,000 of them in London. &#91;68&#93; &#91;69&#93; The [tabloid press](/Tabloid_journalism) sounded the alarm, suggesting that what may have "started as a desperate resort by the genuine homeless" was rapidly escalating, driven by "extremist political groups" who saw "anybody's home" as a potential target. &#91;70&#93; While the [Metropolitan Police Special Branch](/Special_Branch_(Metropolitan_Police)) dedicated resources to infiltrate and monitor the squatting scene, their assessment concluded that squatting "did not exist as movement." They identified anarchists as the largest political tendency among squatting activists, but considered them neither particularly "unifying" nor a significant challenge, except for those with "affiliations to Iberia or South America." &#91;72&#93;

Anarchists have remained a visible presence in the squatting movement. In response to the increasing criminalization of squatting, they have occupied non-residential properties—vacant shops, pubs, offices, cinemas, churches, warehouses—where the issue of criminal trespass is less immediate. &#91;73&#93; &#58;&#8202;6&#8202; &#91;74&#93; These occupations have served not only as homeless shelters but also as social centers and venues. In London, however, the law against criminal trespass has been openly defied. A group calling itself the Autonomous Nation of Anarchist Libertarians (ANAL) has occupied a series of luxury mansions to draw attention to the housing crisis and the scandal of empty buildings. In March 2015, they occupied the seven-story former [Institute of Directors](/Institute_of_Directors) building on [Pall Mall](/Pall_Mall,_London), claiming it was the seventeenth property they had occupied in the area. &#91;75&#93;

#### Anti-war, anti-globalisation, protests

The American anthropologist and activist [David Graeber](/David_Graeber) argues that many direct action protests are inherently anarchist in nature: &#91;76&#93;

> The very notion of direct action, with its rejection of a politics which appeals to governments to modify their behaviour, in favour of physical intervention against state power in a form that itself prefigures an alternative—all of this emerges directly from the libertarian tradition.

Based on this premise, and without counting the number of participants who self-identify as "anarchists," Graeber identifies a significant anarchist presence in protests against the [First](/Gulf_War) and [Second Gulf Wars](/Iraq_War), and in the broader [anti-globalisation movement](/Anti-globalization_movement) in both Britain and the United States. &#91;76&#93; The decentralized, leaderless structure and emphasis on direct democracy within the international [Occupy movement](/Occupy_movement) drew inspiration from anarchist principles and practices. Its core concerns regarding economic inequality and corporate influence also align with anarchist critiques of capitalism and the state. &#91;77&#93;

In March 2009, anarchist groups in London participated in the ["Put People First" march](/2009_G20_London_summit_protests) through central London, protesting against [G20](/G20) policies. The anarchist contingent, calling themselves "G20 Meltdown," declared April 1st "Financial Fools Day" and organized a "carnival" outside the [Bank of England](/Bank_of_England). &#91;78&#93; A smaller group, breaking away from a crowd of 7,000, vandalized an office of the bailed-out [Royal Bank of Scotland](/Royal_Bank_of_Scotland). A professional photographer claimed to have witnessed individuals he suspected were police "[agents provocateurs](/Agents_provocateurs)" instigating the violence. &#91;79&#93; In March 2011, a massive anti-[austerity](/Austerity) demonstration, organized by the [TUC](/Trades_Union_Congress) in London and attended by half a million people, was partially "hijacked" by anarchists who attacked [The Ritz Hotel](/The_Ritz_Hotel,_London), smashed the windows of [West End](/West_End_of_London) banks, and clashed with the police. They justified their actions by citing the failure of the larger anti-war march in 2003 to prevent the [invasion of Iraq](/2003_invasion_of_Iraq), suggesting that political change was not "predicated on being right and winning a debate." &#91;80&#93;

